teams.name: Friends of Bob Harris
teams.loan_because:
After stumbling into a job as a luxury travel writer, I saw so much poverty that I decided to turn those paychecks into Kiva loans. Then I visited a bunch of clients, who were amazing, and I've written a book about it called "The International Bank of Bob" (Walker/Bloomsbury, March 5, 2013).

I hope the book will get more people to feel a greater understanding of Kiva, a better appreciation of the role of microfinance, and most of all, more connected to the rest of the world.
teams.description: People who realize that if we switched places with the recipients, they'd loan to us just as happily.  So, fair's fair.

teams.name: Sonya + Adam's 2013 Wedding Registry
teams.loan_because: we're getting married in October 2013 and, since we're blessed with bursting cupboards and closets in our home already, we thought we'd offer a charity registry as an alternative to our traditional registries.  Kiva is a great organization -- your loaned funds work to help entrepreneurs around the world, who will then repay your loan, which can then be put towards another person.  Pretty cool, right?  Sort of like me and Adam's love for each other (I can hear your groans from here:)).
teams.description: To make a team loan, first click the "join" button on the right, then (if you're not already a member) sign up to be a member of Kiva. Then you might check out the link to "loans" listed above to see where the team has loaned so far, or by clicking the "lend" tab at the very top you can browse to find the entrepreneur whose venture speaks to you. Or, if you prefer, give a Kiva gift certificate (available under "kiva gifts" up top), and Adam and I will be thrilled to select an entrepreneur on your behalf.

http://apluskiva.wordpress.com/

teams.name: Ethnobotanists
teams.loan_because: To alleviate poverty and hardship
teams.description:
We are a loosely affiliated group of people who come from a diverse range of backgrounds. Our common passion is the recognition that humans, as a species, have evolved alongside plants to get where we are today, and that we could not have done so without them (whether it be for food, medicine, spiritual or cultural development, shelter, or even just aesthetics). We cherish the ongoing roles these plants play in our lives, and defend our right to continue and nurture this relationship.

Lenders from this team make loans with the goal of improving the lives of people less fortunate than themselves. A significant portion of the funds raised for these loans come from selling, trading, and sharing plants, with the vision of further extending the growth these plants have brought to human existence.

teams.name: Intel Small Things Challenge
teams.loan_because: Every small, individual action can make a big difference -- especially if millions participate. A modest micro-loan will give an entrepreneur a hand-up to start a new business and provide for his or her family.
teams.description:
Intel is the corporate sponsor of the Small Things Challenge. The company is providing financial support as well as providing opportunities throughout the year to increase global awareness for the issues addressed by the Small Things Challenge – providing opportunities so children in developing countries can attend primary school and their parents can earn higher incomes.
The Intel Small Things Challenge builds upon Intel’s 40 years of active involvement in education. The company is again investing about $100 million in education in 2009.
